'''Jesse Carmichael Randall''' (born 19 August 2002) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

== Club career ==

=== Early career ===
Randall began his senior career in New Zealand, playing regional football with [[Island Bay United AFC|Island Bay United]] in 2018, where he scored 15 goals in 16 appearances. He moved to [[North Wellington AFC|North Wellington]] in 2019, scoring 41 goals in 44 league matches, and spent time on loan with [[Tasman United]] and [[Hawke's Bay United FC|Hawke's Bay United]] during the 2019–20 and 2020–21 seasons respectively. In 2022, Randall signed for [[Wellington Olympic AFC|Wellington Olympic]], where he scored 17 goals in 22 appearances in the [[New Zealand National League|National League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/130941044/wellington-footballer-with-an-eye-for-goal-gets-shot-at-pro-contract-in-england|title=Wellington footballer with an eye for goal|publisher=stuff.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.org/2020/12/23/young-jesse-randall-in-top-form-for-hawkes-bay-united/|title=Jesse Randall on top form for Hawke's Bay United|date=23 December 2020|publisher=oceaniafootballcenter.org}}</ref>

In January 2023, it was reported that Randall was training with [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] on a week-long trial.<ref>{{cite web |date=11 January 2023 |title=Olympic winger Jesse Randall training with English League One club Barnsley |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2023/01/11/olympic-winger-jesse-randall-training-with-english-league-one-club-barnsley/ |access-date=1 April 2026 |publisher=Friends of Football}}</ref> In March 2023, Randall moved to the United States, signing with [[USL Championship]] side [[Charleston Battery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2023/04/26/u-20-international-jesse-randall-makes-big-impression-in-first-start-for-us-club/|title=Jesse Randall makes big impression|date=26 April 2023|publisher=friendsoffootballnz.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uslchampionship.com/news_article/show/1265846-battery-bring-aboard-new-zealand-youth-international-jesse-randall|title=Battery bring aboard New Zealand youth international Jesse Randall|author=USLChampionship com Staff|date=22 March 2023|website=USL Championship}}</ref> He made seven appearances for the club before returning to New Zealand later that year, rejoining Wellington Olympic and scoring seven goals in eight matches in the 2024 season.

=== Auckland FC ===
On 29 May 2024, Randall was announced as one of the first signings for [[Auckland FC|Auckland FC's]] inaugural season.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Auckland FC unveil first signings ahead of debut season|url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/auckland-fc-unveil-first-signings-ahead-of-debut-season/|website=Auckland|date=2024-05-29|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en-US|last=}}</ref> He was predominantly deployed as a striker alongside [[Guillermo May]] during the 2024–25 campaign. Randall scored his first goal for the club in a 6–1 win over [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] and went on to record three goals and one assist in his debut [[A-League Men]] season.<ref>{{Cite web|title=RD 20 Match Report: Auckland FC 6 – 1 Wellington Phoenix|url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/rd-20-match-report-auckland-fc-6-1-wellington-phoenix/|website=Auckland|date=2025-02-22|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en-US|last=}}</ref>

Randall later scored three goals in four [[Australia Cup]] appearances after being shifted to a left-wing role, including a goal after just 30 seconds in a 4–1 victory over [[Gold Coast Knights F.C.|Gold Coast Knights]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Post Match Report: Gold Coast Knights 0 – 4 Auckland FC|url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/post-match-report-gold-coast-knights-0-4-auckland-fc/|website=Auckland|date=2025-07-29|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en-US|last=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Post Match Report: South Melbourne 0 – 3 Auckland FC|url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/post-match-report-south-melbourne-0-3-auckland-fc/|website=Auckland|date=2025-08-13|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en-US|last=}}</ref> He scored his first goal of the following season in a 1–0 win over Western Sydney Wanderers.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Auckland FC's Steve Corica happy with side's start to men's A-League season|url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2025/10/31/auckland-fcs-steve-corica-happy-with-sides-start-to-mens-a-league-season/|website=Friends of Football|date=2025-10-31|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en-NZ|last=}}</ref> Randall finished the A-League season with nine goals and six assists,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jesse Randall (Forward, Auckland FC) : |url=https://www.ultimatealeague.com/player/?player_id=1710 |access-date=2026-04-29 |website=Ultimate A-League |language=en}}</ref> including two goals and one assist in Auckland's 5–0 win over Wellington Phoenix at [[Sky Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=McMillan |first=Cameron |title=Auckland FC hand Phoenix worst home defeat after goalie's howler |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/auckland-fc/auckland-fc-rout-wellington-phoenix-5-0-in-record-a-league-derby-win/SY6YZMELDVAF5KJZLQAKYXQXUU/ |access-date=2026-04-29 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Rollo |first=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix humiliated as own goal sparks 5-0 thrashing by Auckland FC |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360941786/auckland-fc-embarrass-wellington-phoenix-one-sided-derby-after-goalkeepers-horror-moment |access-date=2026-04-29 |website=www.stuff.co.nz}}</ref> He was later awarded both Auckland FC Members’ Player of the Season and the club’s A-League Men Players’ Player of the Season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sherry |first=Samuel |title=Auckland FC hand out awards to club's top players ahead of elimination final |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/auckland-fc/auckland-fc-awards-night-jesse-randall-takes-double-verstraete-named-mvp/36EH32IJMBD77KZ3CMG3YYSQDQ/ |access-date=2026-04-30 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=rcuthbertson |date=2026-04-28 |title=Auckland FC's Knight of Celebration |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/auckland-fcs-knight-of-celebration/ |access-date=2026-04-29 |website=Auckland |language=en-US}}</ref> Randall was later included in the [[Professional Footballers Australia]] (PFA) A-League Team of the Season, alongside teammates [[Sam Cosgrove]] and [[Francis de Vries]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=D'Urbano |first=Nicholas |date=2026-05-19 |title=Devenish-Meares captains star-studded PFA A-League Men Team of the Season |url=https://pfa.net.au/news/devenish-meares-captains-star-studded-pfa-a-league-men-team-of-the-season/ |access-date=2026-05-19 |website=The PFA |language=en-AU}}</ref>

Randall recorded two assists during Auckland FC's run in the [[A-League Finals Series|finals series]]. He assisted Guillermo May from a corner in a 1–1 draw with [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] in the elimination final, a match Auckland later won on penalties.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Auckland FC beat Melbourne City in penalty shootout |url=https://www.1news.co.nz/2026/05/02/auckland-fc-beat-melbourne-city-in-penalty-shootout/ |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=1News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Auckland FC's Dan Hall on how they beat Melbourne City on penalties to advance to A-League Men semifinals |url=https://www.thepost.co.nz/sport/360997171/auckland-fcs-dan-hall-how-they-beat-melbourne-city-penalties-advance-league-men-semifinals |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=www.thepost.co.nz}}</ref> Randall also assisted [[Logan Rogerson]] for Auckland's third goal in a 3–0 win over [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]] in the second leg of the semi-finals, sealing a 4–1 aggregate victory and securing the club's first appearance in the [[A-League Men Grand Final|A-League Grand Final]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=ibenet |date=2026-05-15 |title=Semi Final Leg 2 Match Report: Adelaide United 0 - 3 Auckland FC (1-4 Aggregate) |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/semi-final-leg-2-match-report-adelaide-united-0-3-auckland-fc-1-4-aggregate/ |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=Auckland |language=en-US}}</ref> Randall's 50th and final A-League Men appearance for Auckland came in the [[2026 A-League Men Grand Final]], a 1–0 victory over [[Sydney FC]], as Auckland became the first New Zealand club to win the A-League Men Championship.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Voerman |first=Andrew |date=2026-05-23 |title=Auckland FC make history with A-League Men grand final win over Sydney FC |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360979770/auckland-fc-make-history-league-men-grand-final-win-over-sydney-fc |access-date=2026-05-23 |website=Stuff |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Burgess |first=Michael |title=Champions! Auckland FC win A-League title |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/auckland-fc/auckland-fc-v-sydney-fc-live-updates-a-league-men-grand-final/WHAAI5ZPFFH55JMEHIVR62PHVM/ |access-date=2026-05-23 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref> Randall started all 30 matches during the season, scoring nine goals and recording six assists. His departure was confirmed by Auckland FC on 28 May 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2026-05-28 |title=Jesse Randall say's his Farewells to Auckland |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/jesse-randall-says-his-farewells-to-auckland/ |access-date=2026-05-28 |website=Auckland |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Dundee United ===
On 30 January 2026, [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] announced that they had signed Randall on a pre-contract agreement. He agreed to a two-year deal, with the club holding an option to extend the contract by a further year.<ref>{{Cite web|title=UNITED SNAP UP NEW ZEALAND INTERNATIONAL JESSE RANDALL ON PRE-CONTRACT AGREEMENT|url=https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/9256/UNITED-SNAP-UP-NEW-ZEALAND-INTERNATIONAL-JESSE-RANDALL-ON-PRE-CONTRACT-AGREEMENT.html|website=Dundee United Football Club|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Dundee United swoop for Auckland FC winger Jesse Randall |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360932152/dundee-united-swoop-auckland-fc-winger-jesse-randall |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=www.stuff.co.nz}}</ref>

== International career ==

=== Youth ===
Randall has represented [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand U-17]] and [[New Zealand national under-23 football team|New Zealand U-23]] at youth level.<ref>{{cite web |title=U-23's through to OFC Men's Olympic Qualifier final |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/132637 |access-date=1 April 2026 |publisher=New Zealand Football}}</ref><ref name="U23callup">{{cite web |date=21 August 2023 |title=Battery's Jesse Randall called up for New Zealand U-23's Olympic Qualifying |url=https://www.uslchampionship.com/news_article/show/1282005 |access-date=1 April 2026 |publisher=USL Championship}}</ref> He was part of the New Zealand squad at the [[2024 Summer Olympics]], scoring against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] during the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand U23 1-4 USA U23 (Jul 27, 2024) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/699813 |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Brennan |first=Joe |date=2024-07-27 |title=New Zealand - USA: summary, score, goals, highlights 2024 Olympics soccer |url=https://en.as.com/olympic_games/new-zealand-usa-live-online-score-stats-and-updates-2024-olympics-soccer-n/ |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=AS USA |language=en-us}}</ref>

=== Senior ===
On 18 June 2024 Randall made his debut for the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national football team]] during a 3–1 win over the [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] in the [[2024 OFC Men's Nations Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Young All Whites side win opening game at OFC Men's Nations Cup with six players making debuts |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref> He scored his first international goal on 30 June 2024 in a 3–0 win over [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]] in the final, also providing an assist in the match.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2024-06-30 |title=All Whites win sixth OFC Men's Nations Cup with 3-0 win against Vanuatu |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2024/06/30/all-whites-win-sixth-ofc-mens-nations-cup-with-3-0-win-against-vanuatu/ |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=Friends of Football |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

Randall featured for New Zealand during their [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand vs Fiji 7-0 {{!}} Third Round - Semi-final {{!}} FIFA World Cup 26 |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/match-centre/match/520/288319/288327/400019142 |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=www.fifa.com}}</ref> He was part of the squad during matches that contributed to New Zealand securing qualification.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Squad Named for All Whites FIFA World Cup Oceania Qualifiers this March |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-03-11 |title=Just one change to All Whites squad as they attempt to secure World Cup spot |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/sport/544439/just-one-change-to-all-whites-squad-as-they-attempt-to-secure-world-cup-spot?.com |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=RNZ |language=en-nz}}</ref>

On 30 March 2026, Randall scored his second senior international goal in a 4–1 victory over [[Chile national football team|Chile]] during the [[FIFA Series]]. The result marked New Zealand's first win over a South American ([[CONMEBOL]]) opponent.<ref>{{Cite web |title=All Whites Defeat Chile To Make History At Eden Park In FIFA Series |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Harrison |first=Brayden |title=All Whites bounce back with ruthless 4-1 victory against Chile |url=https://www.1news.co.nz/2026/03/30/all-whites-bounce-back-with-ruthless-4-1-victory-against-chile/ |access-date=2026-03-31 |website=1News |language=en}}</ref> 

On 14 May, Randall was named in the 26-man New Zealand squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand Squad Named for FIFA World Cup 2026 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Powell |first=Alex |title=Wood, Smith make history as All Whites name 26-man World Cup squad |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/football-world-cup/fifa-world-cup-live-updates-all-whites-name-squad-for-2026-tournament/VO65EA66YRHJTDPOMT4V2RYVZ4/ |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

